<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-032-105 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 432 423</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  Oct 20 1991 p1F(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Carnal computing: game maker wants box warning labels for adultsoftware. (Ken Williams, president of Sierra On-Line Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Oldenburg, Don.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ken Williams, president of Sierra On-Line Inc, a softwarepublishing firm that makes sexually explicit computer games, wantsto label computer games similarly to movies with ratings like G,PG, R and X. When Williams brought up the issue to the standardscommittee of the Software Publishers Association, however, theidea was abandoned in the face of conflicting attitudes; somepeople resisted all forms of censorship, while others wanted tocompletely ban violent or sexual computer games.andP;  Explicit games,however, are an expanding market.andP;  Sierra On-Line sells theLeisure Suit Larry software series, in which users help Larrypursue computerized affairs.andP;  The $59 box has a warning labelstating that the game 'contains adult subject matter.' Parentalguidance is suggested.' Sexxy Software produces the $79SexxCapades game, which is similar to Monopoly, except sexualfavors replace property and hotels.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Sierra On-Line Inc. (Products).andO;Ticker:    SIER.andO;Product:   Leisure Suit Larry (Computer game) (Usage)SexxCapades (Computer game) (Usage).andO;Topic:     EntertainmentAdultsComputer GamesSoftware Publishers AssociationCensorshipLabelsMarket AnalysisSocial Issues.andO;Person:    Williams, Ken (Attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>